file?language=EN>Mheddik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 93<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/18/02 9:38:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=249.topic&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Also</span><hr size=1> What, exactly, IS the definition of 'power gamer'. For example, take, say, a retired person, who can play 16 hours a day, enjoys doing so, and does so. He will almost certainly level faster than someone who plays an hour every other night. In comparison to the person who plays 3.5 hours per week, he will almost definitely gain levels FAR faster. And that will be so even if 75 percent of his time is sitting in the bar in FP telling folks stories of his exploits the other 25 percent of the time. And he can be an avid RPer as well.<br>
<br>
Now take someone who actually has that much time and RPs someone who avidly seeks 'power', e.g. more powerful spells, weapons, whatever. There certainly have been such characters in fantasy literature and it is not impossible to conceive of someone roleplaying such a character. Even to the extent that if they can get some druid or cleric or enchanter or whatever to do their bidding and facilitate their acquisition of power (read: leveling), that they would do so in a heartbeat. Perhaps they are thinking 'Foolish druid. Yes, you help me gain this power and I shall someday repay you...with death!'<br>
<br>
Who is to say that that cannot be roleplaying? Are we to understand that you are the one who defines what is and what is not roleplaying? What violates it and what does not? What actions we can perform, what motivations we can have for those actions? I don't think so. I am an adult, and fully capable of making such determinations on my own and not only do I not need some Big Brother type looking over my shoulder and telling me how I should play, I sorely resent it when people try to do so.<br>
<br>
People who annoy me I put on ignore and pretend they don't exist. If that doesn't work for you, well boo hoo. But in no way, shape or form will I have my actions dictated by another person. Ultimately *I* am responsible for my actions, so I will decide what those actions are, and bear full responsibility for them, for good or for ill. I don't need a 'roleplaying parent', I don't want one, and I won't accept one. If you try to be one, you will be one of those I ignore and pretend does not exist. Which *does* work for me.<br>
<br>
Coriolis of Erudin, Firiona Vie, Beguiler<br>
